  "summary": "# Security Analysis Report: fastapi-0.65.1\n\n## Executive Summary\nIdentified a **CRITICAL** CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) vulnerability in FastAPI's core routing mechanism that could allow attackers to bypass CSRF protections on state-changing operations.\n\n## Critical Vulnerability: CSRF via JSON Body Parsing Without Content-Type Validation\n\n### CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)\n\n**Severity:** CRITICAL\n\n**Location:** `fastapi/routing.py` lines 182-184\n\n### Vulnerability Description\nFastAPI's routing layer parses request bodies (via `await request.body()` and `await request.json()`) in async request handlers **without validating the Content-Type header first**. This allows attackers to craft CSRF attacks that bypass the browser's same-origin policy protections.\n\n### Technical Details\nThe vulnerable code pattern found:\n- **Line 182:** `await request.body()` - Parses request body without Content-Type check\n- **Line 184:** `await request.json()` - Parses JSON without Content-Type check\n- Both occur in async function `app()` in the routing module\n\n### Attack Scenario\n1. Application uses cookie-based authentication (confirmed via findings in `fastapi/security/api_key.py` line 63 and `fastapi/dependencies/utils.py` line 565)\n2. Application has state-changing endpoints (POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE) - confirmed at lines 788, 838, 888, 1038 in routing.py\n3. Attacker crafts a malicious HTML form with `Content-Type: text/plain` or uses fetch with `no-cors` mode\n4. Browser sends cookies automatically with the request\n5. FastAPI parses the body as JSON regardless of Content-Type\n6. State-changing operation executes with user's authentication\n\n### Impact\n- **Authentication Bypass:** Attackers can perform actions on behalf of authenticated users\n- **Data Manipulation:** Unauthorized state changes (create, update, delete operations)\n- **Privilege Escalation:** If admin users are targeted, full system compromise possible\n\n### Affected Components\n- Core routing mechanism (`fastapi/routing.py`)\n- All endpoints using POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE methods\n- Applications relying on cookie-based authentication\n\n### Recommendations\n1. **Immediate:** Validate Content-Type header before parsing request bodies\n2. **Implement:** CSRF token validation for state-changing operations\n3. **Enforce:** Strict Content-Type checking (application/json only for JSON endpoints)\n4. **Add:** SameSite cookie attribute for session cookies\n5. **Consider:** Moving to header-based authentication (Bearer tokens) instead of cookies\n\n## Additional Findings\n\n### Authentication Patterns Identified\n- Cookie-based authentication in `fastapi/security/api_key.py`\n- Header-based authentication in multiple security modules\n- OAuth2 implementations that may be affected by CSRF\n\n## Package Classification\n- **Type:** Web Framework\n- **Layer:** Application Framework, HTTP Routing, Security\n\n## Conclusion\nThis is a **critical architectural vulnerability** in FastAPI version 0.65.1 that affects the core request handling mechanism. Any application using cookie-based authentication with state-changing endpoints is potentially vulnerable to CSRF attacks. Immediate patching is recommended.",
